Discrete discounting as introduced in the previous section is common business practice. However, continuous discounting by means of an interest rate ϱ that is applied continuously (at infinitely small time steps) to a capital stock Kt in order to add compound interest is easier to handle in mathematics than discrete discounting. Continuous capital growth Kt is described by means of Euler’s number e (=2.71828…):6.9Kt=K0eρt⇒dKtdt=ρK0eρt⇒dKtdt=ρKt⇒dKtKtdt=K•Kt=ρ.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {K}_t={K}_0{\mathrm{e}}^{\rho t}\Rightarrow \frac{\mathrm{d}{K}_t}{\mathrm{d}t}=\rho {K}_0{\mathrm{e}}^{\rho t}\Rightarrow \frac{\mathrm{d}{K}_t}{\mathrm{d}t}=\rho {K}_t\Rightarrow \frac{\frac{\mathrm{d}{K}_t}{K_t}}{\mathrm{d}t}=\frac{\overset{\bullet }{K}}{K_t}=\rho . $$\end{document}

The unit of the capital growth rate ϱ is % divided by the time unit for which the capital growth function has been calibrated, e.g. %/year. Applying the formula for continuous compounding, one can again ask for the present value B0 of a benefit Bt that will be available in t years:6.10Bt=B0eρt⇒B0=Bte−ρt.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
